{"folder":"t4OYJx9NxJtOfun3","name":"Deductions","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Deductions","type":"text","_id":"ccxpu2HQ6bHsYs1R","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>This journal is available for players to record their deductions. You should duplicate it and use the duplicate to avoid overwriting it if you reimport the adventure.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"sort":500000,"ownership":{"default":3,"dBogmx4vpeLG8Oap":3,"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6":3},"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.2.2","coreVersion":"10.303","createdTime":1683049982055,"modifiedTime":1691035273336,"lastModifiedBy":"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6"},"_id":"BwsXxrfYIEmxaSGH"}
{"folder":"t4OYJx9NxJtOfun3","name":"Adventure Links","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Link to Ambitious Assassins","type":"text","_id":"Qy2hi9lDgt7tiKFv","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Melvin, the urchin begging outside the station, is a member of the Sewer Rats (see @UUID[JournalEntry.r8I96QUqyrC6APWw]{The Case of the Ambitious Assassins} @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.PD0Ece26PAdcs3P6]{import}). </p><p>He's keeping an eye on the station for the Sewer Rats. If the officers have been kind to him, he will truthfully answer questions about the Sewer Rats. He doesn't know much about the leaders and activities, but he can tell them how to find them in the sewers.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Link to Voluptuous Vampire","type":"text","_id":"4dHoMorB4mkeLY1E","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>This critter is used in the @UUID[JournalEntry.v1pMlwbFDT6Pk3cQ]{Case of the Voluptuous Vampire} @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.wfrcaCsIR9P5ErNu]{import}.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"sort":325000,"ownership":{"default":0,"dBogmx4vpeLG8Oap":3,"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6":3},"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.2.2","coreVersion":"10.303","createdTime":1686337368184,"modifiedTime":1691035273342,"lastModifiedBy":"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6"},"_id":"DiRc3rlZH4I6oazk"}
{"folder":"t4OYJx9NxJtOfun3","name":"Temple of Truth and Justice","pages":[{"sort":-100000,"name":"Introduction","type":"text","_id":"1Frx5zaz9PuII9BQ","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>The Flying Squad is aligned with the Temple of Truth and Justice, whose members often provide clerical services to the squad. The squad's supervisor, Capt. Larkspur, is a member of the Temple.</p><p>The Temple is a interdenominational religious order devoted to the pursuit of truth and justice. It is not dedicated to a single deity, but rather all deities that promote these virtues.</p><p>The name Truth and Justice is representative of broader goals: sometimes \"law and order\" does not mean the same thing as \"truth and justice.\" Followers of the Temple can be of any good or neutral alignment, as long as they esteem the ideals of truth and justice.</p><p><em>The Temple's adherents include devotees of Tyr in Waterdeep. If you're using the Forgotten Realms or another campaign feel free to designate an existing religious order to the role of the Temple of Truth and Justice.</em></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":0,"name":"Services Provided","type":"text","_id":"vj8IAe1LlNglZSkI","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>The Temple of Truth and Justice provides services, including spell casting and some potions, to members of the Flying Squad at cost, which is typically the price of any material components, and is subject to availability.</p><p>To receive these services at these rates officer must show their insignia of rank.</p><h2>Spell Availability</h2><p>\"Availability\" is the chance that a cleric of the appropriate level is present and has the spell prepared. This is dependent on spell level and time of day.</p><p>The percentage chance that a spell is available is:</p><p style=\"text-align:center\">100 - 5 x level - 4 x &lt;hours since sunrise&gt;<br />with a minimum chance of 10%</p><p>The hour after sunrise is spent in meditation and preparation, and spells are not yet prepared, so it is considered 24 hours since sunrise.</p><p>The chance that a level 2 <em>cure wounds</em> spell is available two hours after sunrise is 100 - 5 x 2 - 4 x 2 = 82%. The chance that a level 5 <em>raise dead</em> spell is available 12 hours after sunrise is 100 - 5 x 5 - 4 x 12 = 22%. A <em>resurrection</em> spell in the middle of the night (4 hours before sunrise) has a 100 - 5 x 7 - 4 x 20 = -15% chance, but there is still a minimum chance of 10%.</p><p>If the squad requires multiple spells at a time the chance is decreased by an additional 5% for each additional spell cast, and there is no minimum chance — the temple runs out of spells when the chance is zero.</p><h2>Spell Casting Fees</h2><p>Spells that require concentration, such as <em>protection from energy</em> are unavailable. Divination spells, such as <em>augury, commune, clairvoyance,</em> are also not available.</p><p>The fee for a spell that requires a material component will be waived if the component is provided.</p><p><em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.Opwh2PdX4runSBlm]{Aid} </em>no charge</p><p><em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.uUWb1wZgtMou0TVP]{Cure wounds}</em> no charge</p><p><em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.VtCXMdyM6mAdIJZb]{Death ward}</em> no charge</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.ghXTfe7sgCbgf1Q8]{Detect Magic} no charge</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.2skfDtglk1mGrb3l]{Detect Poison and Disease} no charge</p><p><em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.15Fa6q1nH27XfbR8]{Dispel magic} </em>no charge</p><p><em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.WzvJ7G3cqvIubsLk]{Greater restoration}</em> 100 gp (100 gp worth of diamond dust)</p><p><em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.F0GsG0SJzsIOacwV]{Lesser restoration}: </em>no charge</p><p><em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.MOEmz9N0j0QPkKEE]{Prayer of healing}</em> no charge</p><p><em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.AGFMPAmuzwWO6Dfz]{Raise dead}</em> 500 gp (500-gp diamond)</p><p><em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.9kGrFXnLiRg3Xnbo]{Regenerate} </em>no charge</p><p><em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.XZhdgVK3cLoxNCQl]{Remove curse}</em> no charge</p><p><em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.jhhT9PsHy5A7EojO]{Resurrection}</em> 1,000 gp (1,000-gp diamond)</p><p><em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.CylBa7jR8DSbo8Z3]{Zone of truth}</em> no charge</p><h2>Potions</h2><p>Potions are also subject to availability based on their rarity. The chances that a potion is available are:</p><ul><li><p>Common: 80%</p></li><li><p>Uncommon: 60%</p></li><li><p>Rare: 40%</p></li><li><p>Very rare: 20%</p></li></ul><h3>Prices</h3><p>The following potions are most frequently requested. Others may be available; treat them as one level higher rarity.</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.items.ytlsBjYsZ7OBSEBs]{Potion of Healing} 50 gp, common</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.items.L887NdWEP5NqHCrQ]{Potion of Greater Healing} 150 gp, uncommon</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.items.zgZkJAyFAfYmyn11]{Potion of Acid Resistance} 300 gp, uncommon</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.items.Jj4iFQQGvckx8Wsj]{Potion of Fire Resistance} 300 gp, uncommon</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.items.f5chGcpQCi1HYPQw]{Potion of Poison Resistance} 300 gp, uncommon</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.items.5m9ErO9In8Uc5yyf]{Potion of Superior Healing} 450 gp, rare</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.items.JFiSlgcm3uSSBM5t]{Potion of Supreme Healing} 1,350 gp, very rare</p><p></p><p></p><p></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Temple Plan","type":"text","_id":"2LPbQapif0HoxAta","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><em>Activate the @UUID[Macro.eIdHNuMaoMGtLWum]{Temple of Truth and Justice} scene is in the Flying Squad folder of the Scenes tab.</em></p><p>The temple is situated on a raised podium, surrounded by tall white marble columns and white marble floors.</p><h1>1. Cella</h1><p>The cella, or main chamber of the temple, houses the symbol of the order: the scales of truth and justice. Ever-burning brazier stand on either side of the scales. The altar stands before the scales, with fountains on either side.</p><p>Holy water dispensers are on either side of the doors. An alms box is in the southwest corner.</p><p>Two @UUID[Actor.exeauojQfSmGtQmm]{acolytes} are on duty here at all times. They will call upon the priests who can provide @UUID[.vj8IAe1LlNglZSkI]{services} if they cannot handle the request themselves.</p><h1>2-4. Consultation Rooms</h1><p>@UUID[Actor.uziXsKHyjt2p6DMv]{Priests of the temple} receive petitioners here, providing medical care and casting spells.</p><h1>5-7. Guest Quarters</h1><p>Traveling priests stay here, as well as patients recovering from the effects of <em>raise dead </em>and other debilitating conditions<em>.</em></p><h1>8. High Priest's Room</h1><p>The @UUID[Actor.RDXqO0eYMKZ0kugt]{head of the temple} resides here.</p><h1>9-13. Priests' Quarters</h1><p>The other temple priests live here.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"sort":300000,"ownership":{"default":2,"dBogmx4vpeLG8Oap":3,"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6":3},"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.2.2","coreVersion":"10.303","createdTime":1683113978913,"modifiedTime":1691035273338,"lastModifiedBy":"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6"},"_id":"HkUyKycM2w2ODySP"}
{"folder":"t4OYJx9NxJtOfun3","name":"Street Scene","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Street Scene","type":"text","_id":"wZmbJys2kVuGbqWf","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Use this generic @UUID[Macro.S4IAmEdaJOrM0QyM]{street scene} when you need to create a quick encounter on the streets.</p><p>You may wish to duplicate the scene before populating it with tokens.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"sort":450000,"ownership":{"default":0,"dBogmx4vpeLG8Oap":3,"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6":3},"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.2.2","coreVersion":"10.303","createdTime":1687196211323,"modifiedTime":1691035273343,"lastModifiedBy":"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6"},"_id":"Hq2GxtUv1h353JjG"}
{"folder":"t4OYJx9NxJtOfun3","name":"Spare Mansion","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Mansion","type":"text","_id":"rVs6F3MhiHDQA1Ud","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Use @UUID[Macro.vTqnaFLL3SLtcnZ8]{this map} if the squad needs to visit a wealthy person and you don't have another map ready.</p><p>You may wish to duplicate it before populating it with tokens.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"sort":375000,"ownership":{"default":0,"dBogmx4vpeLG8Oap":3,"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6":3},"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.2.2","coreVersion":"10.303","createdTime":1686343978823,"modifiedTime":1691035273342,"lastModifiedBy":"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6"},"_id":"JKHUVJg3UAlSIXVA"}
{"name":"To Do","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"New Page","type":"text","_id":"zaNnJPKIRRZ0mJBM","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Dragon Ancestries for Draconic Bloodline — add all colors.</p><p>Add all subclasses for sorcerers and warlocks, and whatever else is missing.</p><p>Look at Tasha's to see if any other subclasses are relevant.</p><p>War Domain</p><p>Light domain.</p><p>Forge.</p><p>Death</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"war domain","type":"text","_id":"c5KaC8RlaJgXGjlT","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<main><div><div><div><div><div><p>Cleric: War Domain</p></div><div><p>War has many manifestations. It can make heroes of ordinary people. It can be desperate and horrific, with acts of cruelty and cowardice eclipsing instances of excellence and courage. In either case, the gods of war watch over warriors and reward them for their great deeds. The clerics of such gods excel in battle, inspiring others to fight the good fight or offering acts of violence as prayers. Gods of war include champions of honor and chivalry (such as Torm, Heironeous, and Kiri-Jolith) as well as gods of destruction and pillage (such as Erythnul, the Fury, Gruumsh, and Ares) and gods of conquest and domination (such as Bane, Hextor, and Maglubiyet). Other war gods (such as Tempus, Nike, and Nuada) take a more neutral stance, promoting war in all its manifestations and supporting warriors in any circumstance.</p><div><div><div><p>Source: Player's Handbook</p><table><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\">War Domain Spells</th></tr><tr><th>Cleric Level</th><th>Spells</th></tr><tr><td>1st</td><td>Divine Favor, Shield of Faith</td></tr><tr><td>3rd</td><td>Magic Weapon, Spiritual Weapon</td></tr><tr><td>5th</td><td>Crusader's Mantle, Spirit Guardians</td></tr><tr><td>7th</td><td>Freedom of Movement, Stoneskin</td></tr><tr><td>9th</td><td>Flame Strike, Hold Monster</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Bonus Proficiency</h3><p>At 1st level, you gain proficiency with martial weapons and heavy armor.</p><h3>War Priest</h3><p>From 1st level, your god delivers bolts of inspiration to you while you are engaged in battle. When you use the Attack action, you can make one weapon attack as a bonus action.</p><p>You can use this feature a number of times equal to your Wisdom modifier (a minimum of once). You regain all expended uses when you finish a long rest.</p><h3>Channel Divinity: Guided Strike</h3><p>Starting at 2nd level, you can use your Channel Divinity to strike with supernatural accuracy. When you make an attack roll, you can use your Channel Divinity to gain a +10 bonus to the roll. You make this choice after you see the roll, but before the DM says whether the attack hits or misses.</p><h3>Channel Divinity: War God's Blessing</h3><p>At 6th level, when a creature within 30 feet of you makes an attack roll, you can use your reaction to grant that creature a +10 bonus to the roll, using your Channel Divinity. You make this choice after you see the roll, but before the DM says whether the attack hits or misses.</p><h3>Divine Strike</h3><p>At 8th level, you gain the ability to infuse your weapon strikes with divine energy. Once on each of your turns when you hit a creature with a weapon attack, you can cause the attack to deal an extra 1d8 damage of the same type dealt by the weapon to the target. When you reach 14th level, the extra damage increases to 2d8.</p><h3>Avatar of Battle</h3><p>At 17th level, you gain resistance to bludgeoning, piercing, and slashing damage from nonmagical attacks.</p></div></div></div></div><div><p></p></div><div><p></p></div></div></div></div></div></main><footer><div><p><br></p></div></footer>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"LIght","type":"text","_id":"Yt4sfMmNN5iVbXrv","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<main><div><div><div><div><div><p>Cleric: Light Domain</p></div><div><p>Gods of light – including Helm, Lathander, Pholtus, Branchala, the Silver Flame, Belenus, Apollo, and Re-Horakhty – promote the ideals of rebirth and renewal, truth, vigilance, and beauty, often using the symbol of the sun. Some of these gods are portrayed as the sun itself or as a charioteer who guides the sun across the sky. Others are tireless sentinels whose eyes pierce every shadow and see through every deception. Some are deities of beauty and artistry, who teach that art is a vehicle for the soul's improvement. Clerics of a god of light are enlightened souls infused with radiance and the power of their gods' discerning vision, charged with chasing away lies and burning away darkness.</p><div><div><div><p>Source: Player's Handbook</p><table><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\">Light Domain Spells</th></tr><tr><th>Cleric Level</th><th>Spells</th></tr><tr><td>1st</td><td>Burning Hands, Faerie Fire</td></tr><tr><td>3rd</td><td>Flaming Sphere, Scorching Ray</td></tr><tr><td>5th</td><td>Daylight, Fireball</td></tr><tr><td>7th</td><td>Guardian of Faith, Wall of Fire</td></tr><tr><td>9th</td><td>Flame Strike, Scrying</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Bonus Cantrip</h3><p>When you choose this domain at 1st level, you gain the Light cantrip if you don't already know it. This cantrip doesn’t count against the number of cleric cantrips you know.</p><h3>Warding Flare</h3><p>Also at 1st level, you can interpose divine light between yourself and an attacking enemy. When you are attacked by a creature within 30 feet of you that you can see, you can use your reaction to impose disadvantage on the attack roll, causing light to flare before the attacker before it hits or misses. An attacker that can't be blinded is immune to this feature.</p><p>You can use this feature a number of times equal to your Wisdom modifier (a minimum of once). You regain all expended uses when you finish a long rest.</p><h3>Channel Divinity: Radiance of the Dawn</h3><p>Starting at 2nd level, you can use your Channel Divinity to harness sunlight, banishing darkness and dealing radiant damage to your foes.</p><p>As an action, you present your holy symbol, and any magical darkness within 30 feet of you is dispelled. Additionally, each hostile creature within 30 feet of you must make a Constitution saving throw. A creature takes radiant damage equal to 2d10 + your cleric level on a failed saving throw, and half as much damage on a successful one. A creature that has total cover from you is not affected.</p><h3>Improved Flare</h3><p>Starting at 6th level, you can also use your Warding Flare feature when a creature that you can see within 30 feet of you attacks a creature other than you.</p><h3>Potent Spellcasting</h3><p>Starting at 8th level, you add your Wisdom modifier to the damage you deal with any cleric cantrip.</p><h3>Corona of Light</h3><p>Starting at 17th level, you can use your action to activate an aura of sunlight that lasts for 1 minute or until you dismiss it using another action. You emit bright light in a 60-foot radius and dim light 30 feet beyond that. Your enemies in the bright light have disadvantage on saving throws against any spell that deals fire or radiant damage.</p></div></div></div></div><div><p></p></div><div><p></p></div></div></div></div></div></main><footer><div><p><br></p></div></footer>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Forge","type":"text","_id":"Wy6KuyEiYU47KImT","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<main><div><div><div><div><div><p>Cleric: Forge Domain</p></div><div><p>The gods of the forge are patrons of artisans who work with metal, from a humble blacksmith who keeps a village in horseshoes and plow blades to the mighty elf artisan whose diamond-tipped arrows of mithral have felled demon lords. The gods of the forge teach that, with patience and hard work, even the most intractable metal can be transformed from a lump of ore to a beautifully wrought object. Clerics of these deities search for objects lost to the forces of darkness, liberate mines overrun by orcs, and uncover rare and wondrous materials necessary to create potent magic items. Followers of these gods take great pride in their work, and they are willing to craft and use heavy armor and powerful weapons to protect them. Deities of this domain include Gond, Reorx, Onatar, Moradin, Hephaestus, and Goibhniu.</p><div><div><div><p>Source: Xanathar's Guide to Everything</p><table><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\">Forge Domain Spells</th></tr><tr><th>Cleric Level</th><th>Spells</th></tr><tr><td>1st</td><td>Identify, Searing Smite</td></tr><tr><td>3rd</td><td>Heat Metal, Magic Weapon</td></tr><tr><td>5th</td><td>Elemental Weapon, Protection from Energy</td></tr><tr><td>7th</td><td>Fabricate, Wall of Fire</td></tr><tr><td>9th</td><td>Animate Objects, Creation</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Bonus Proficiencies</h3><p>When you choose this domain at 1st level, you gain proficiency with heavy armor and smith's tools.</p><h3>Blessing of the Forge</h3><p>At 1st level, you gain the ability to imbue magic into a weapon or armor. At the end of a long rest, you can touch one nonmagical object that is a suit of armor or a simple or martial weapon. Until the end of your next long rest or until you die, the object becomes a magic item, granting a +1 bonus to AC if it's armor or a +1 bonus to attack and damage rolls if it's a weapon.</p><p>Once you use this feature, you can't use it again until you finish a long rest.</p><h3>Channel Divinity: Artisan's Blessing</h3><p>Starting at 2nd level, you can use your Channel Divinity to create simple items.</p><p>You conduct an hour-long ritual that crafts a nonmagical item that must include some metal: a simple or martial weapon, a suit of armor, ten pieces of ammunition, a set of tools, or another metal object. The creation is completed at the end of the hour, coalescing in an unoccupied space of your choice on a surface within 5 feet of you.</p><p>The thing you create can be something that is worth no more than 100 gp. As part of this ritual, you must lay out metal, which can include coins, with a value equal to the creation. The metal irretrievably coalesces and transforms into the creation at the ritual's end, magically forming even nonmetal parts of the creation.</p><p>The ritual can create a duplicate of a nonmagical item that contains metal, such as a key, if you possess the original during the ritual.</p><h3>Soul of the Forge</h3><p>Starting at 6th level, your mastery of the forge grants you special abilities:</p><ul><li>You gain resistance to fire damage.</li></ul><ul><li>While wearing heavy armor, you gain a +1 bonus to AC.</li></ul><h3>Divine Strike</h3><p>At 8th level, you gain the ability to infuse your weapon strikes with the fiery power of the forge. Once on each of your turns when you hit a creature with a weapon attack, you can cause the attack to deal an extra 1d8 fire damage to the target. When you reach 14th level, the extra damage increases to 2d8.</p><h3>Saint of Forge and Fire</h3><p>At 17th level, your blessed affinity with fire and metal becomes more powerful:</p><ul><li>You gain immunity to fire damage.</li></ul><ul><li>While wearing heavy armor, you have resistance to bludgeoning, piercing, and slashing damage from nonmagical attacks.</li></ul></div></div></div></div><div><p></p></div><div><p></p></div></div></div></div></div></main><footer><div><p><br></p></div></footer>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":500000,"name":"Death","type":"text","_id":"5DDejOsfKqLBTCFp","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<main><div><div><div><div><div><p>Cleric: Death Domain</p></div><div><p>The Death domain is concerned with the forces that cause death, as well as the negative energy that gives rise to undead creatures. Deities such as Chemosh, Myrkul, and Wee Jas are patrons of necromancers, death knights, liches, mummy lords, and vampires. Gods of the Death domain also embody murder (Anubis, Bhaal, and Pyremius), pain (Iuz or Loviatar), disease or poison (Incabulos, Talona, or Morgion), and the underworld (Hades and Hel).</p><div><div><div><p>Source: Dungeon Master's Guide</p><table><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\">Death Domain Spells</th></tr><tr><th>Cleric Level</th><th>Spells</th></tr><tr><td>1st</td><td>False Life, Ray of Sickness</td></tr><tr><td>3rd</td><td>Blindness/Deafness, Ray of Enfeeblement</td></tr><tr><td>5th</td><td>Animate Dead, Vampiric Touch</td></tr><tr><td>7th</td><td>Blight, Death Ward</td></tr><tr><td>9th</td><td>Antilife Shell, Cloudkill</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Bonus Proficiency</h3><p>When you choose this domain at 1st level, you gain proficiency with martial weapons.</p><h3>Reaper</h3><p>At 1st level, you learn one necromancy cantrip of your choice from any spell list. When you cast a necromancy cantrip that normally targets only one creature, the spell can instead target two creatures within range and within 5 feet of each other.</p><h3>Channel Divinity: Touch of Death</h3><p>Starting at 2nd level, you can use Channel Divinity to destroy another creature's life force by touch. When you hit a creature with a melee attack, you can use Channel Divinity to deal extra necrotic damage to the target. The damage equals 5 + twice your cleric level.</p><h3>Inescapable Destruction</h3><p>Starting at 6th level, your ability to channel negative energy becomes more potent. Necrotic damage dealt by your cleric spells and Channel Divinity options ignores resistance to necrotic damage.</p><h3>Divine Strike</h3><p>At 8th level, you gain the ability to infuse your weapon strikes with necrotic energy. Once on each of your turns when you hit a creature with a weapon attack, you can cause the attack to deal an a 1d8 necrotic damage to the target. When you reach 14th level, the extra damage increases to 2d8.</p><h3>Improved Reaper</h3><p>Starting at 17th level, when you cast a necromancy spell of 1st through 5th level that targets only one creature, the spell can instead target two creatures within range and within 5 feet of each other. If the spell consumes its material components, you must provide them for each target.</p></div></div></div></div><div><p></p></div><div><p></p></div></div></div></div></div></main><footer><div><p><br></p></div></footer>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":600000,"name":"swash","type":"text","_id":"lRKugVIo47GRdXz9","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<main><div><div><div><div><div><p>Rogue: Swashbuckler</p></div><div><p>You focus your training on the art of the blade, relying on speed, elegance, and charm in equal parts. While some warriors are brutes clad in heavy armor, your method of fighting looks almost like a performance. Duelists and pirates typically belong to this archetype.</p><p>A Swashbuckler excels in single combat, and can fight with two weapons while safely darting away from an opponent.</p><div><div><div><p>Source: Xanathar's Guide to Everything</p><h3>Fancy Footwork</h3><p>When you choose this archetype at 3rd level, you learn how to land a strike and then slip away without reprisal. During your turn, if you make a melee attack against a creature, that creature can't make opportunity attacks against you for the rest of your turn.</p><h3>Rakish Audacity</h3><p>Starting at 3rd level, your confidence propels you into battle. You can give yourself a bonus to your initiative rolls equal to your Charisma modifier.</p><p>You also gain an additional way to use your Sneak Attack; you don't need advantage on the attack roll to use your Sneak Attack against a creature if you are within 5 feet of it, no other creatures are within 5 feet of you, and you don't have disadvantage on the attack roll. All the other rules for Sneak Attack still apply to you.</p><h3>Panache</h3><p>At 9th level, your charm becomes extraordinarily beguiling. As an action, you can make a Charisma (Persuasion) check contested by a creature's Wisdom (Insight) check. The creature must be able to hear you, and the two of you must share a language.</p><p>If you succeed on the check and the creature is hostile to you, it has disadvantage on attack rolls against targets other than you and can't make opportunity attacks against targets other than you. This effect lasts for 1 minute, until one of your companions attacks the target or affects it with a spell, or until you and the target are more than 60 feet apart.</p><p>If you succeed on the check and the creature isn't hostile to you, it is charmed by you for 1 minute. While charmed, it regards you as a friendly acquaintance. This effect ends immediately if you or your companions do anything harmful to it.</p><h3>Elegant Maneuver</h3><p>Starting at 13th level, you can use a bonus action on your turn to gain advantage on the next Dexterity (Acrobatics) or Strength (Athletics) check you make during the same turn.</p><h3>Master Duelist</h3><p>Beginning at 17th level, your mastery of the blade lets you turn failure into success in combat. If you miss with an attack roll, you can roll it again with advantage. Once you do so, you can't use this feature again until you finish a short or long rest.</p></div></div></div></div><div><p></p></div><div><p></p></div></div></div></div></div></main><footer><div><p><br></p></div></footer>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6":3},"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.2.2","coreVersion":"10.303","createdTime":1690759322430,"modifiedTime":1691171082614,"lastModifiedBy":"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6"},"_id":"KDyHjVRqxYVcLZsi"}
{"name":"The Flying Squad","pages":[{"sort":143750,"name":"Example Characters","type":"text","_id":"6whwN2ZZudLhtTxx","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><strong>Note:</strong> If you use these characters:</p><ul><li><p>First create a Player Characters folder in the Actors tab.</p></li><li><p>Duplicate the character you want to use by right-clicking the character and selecting Duplicate on the dropdown menu.</p></li><li><p>Drag and drop the (Copy) in the Player Characters folder you created.</p></li><li><p>Change the name.</p></li></ul><p>This will ensure that any changes you and the players make to your version of the character will not be lost if you need to reimport the Flying Squad Adventure.</p><h2>Characters</h2><p>Dragonborn Fighter: @UUID[Actor.Gr0qGXdM3JkTzsaV]{Rhogar}</p><p>Rhogar was a bounty hunter who tracked down wanted criminals for a fee. After a few years of that he decided a steady income and regular hours were preferable to staking out tenements in the dead of winter.</p><p>Half Orc Paladin: @UUID[Actor.KtCG62FBuA1toaCf]{Sutha}</p><p>Sutha's father was a weapons merchant who traveled far and wide. He and his wife were murdered by a rival, and Sutha's uncle took her in and raised her. She joined the city watch, motivated by her desire to find justice for her father, whose murderer is still at large.</p><p>Dwarf Cleric: @UUID[Actor.BaCJ0JGl5Zz8xFE6]{Tordek}</p><p>Tordek is a cleric who made a living brewing ale and presiding over weddings (and providing the refreshments for the receptions).</p><p>Drow Bard: @UUID[Actor.f4TVWwtyBWE41fKU]{Vadania}</p><p>Vadania performed in taverns across the city, and stopped quite a few brawls before they got serious. She kept an ear and eye open, and let the city watch know when she heard or saw something untoward in the offing.</p><p>Human Rogue: @UUID[Actor.oH7mkI2zyt2Seywa]{Ælfric}</p><p>Ælfric was a private investigator who was born in poverty but was adopted by a wealthy family who ran over his mother with their carriage when they were being pursued by a group of assassins. After their escape the wife insisted that they go back and tend to the woman. She was dead, but Ælfric, less than a year old, was bundled up in a blanket in her arms, still very, very quiet. And he still is.</p><p>Human Wizard: @UUID[Actor.M6j4VgEEqfZHf6kV]{Gennis}</p><p>Gennis is an evocation wizard who is also an artist. He can draw sketches of suspects after interviewing witnesses.</p><p>Half-elven Sorcerer: @UUID[Actor.SzJMAKwuKppou129]{Naivara}</p><p>Naivara was a merchant who owned a small curio and magic shop that was torched by a jealous rival.</p><p>Half-Elf Fighter/Cleric/Thief: @UUID[Actor.r8BUf0tfWy6fAxqR]{Mindy}</p><p>Mindy started her career with her brother as a guard on caravans. Over time he got into smuggling, and as a good sister she had to join him. She learned a lot about the seamy underside of life, but it troubled her greatly. She frequently went to a temple and prayed for guidance, and eventually saw the light.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Acknowledgments","type":"text","_id":"4ouNpz62jXSWrOoV","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Assets were created with the following resources. We heartily recommend them. They are available at:</p><ul><li><p>Dungeondraft: <a href=\"https://dungeondraft.net/\">https://dungeondraft.net/</a></p></li><li><p>Forgotten Adventures: <a href=\"https://www.forgotten-adventures.net/\">https://www.forgotten-adventures.net/</a></p></li><li><p>2-Minute Tabletop: <a href=\"https://2minutetabletop.com/\">https://2minutetabletop.com/</a></p></li><li><p>TokenTool: <a href=\"https://www.rptools.net/\">https://www.rptools.net/</a></p></li></ul><p>Some character portraits and scene art created with AI at:</p><ul><li><p><a href=\"https://bing.com/create\">bing.com/create</a></p></li><li><p><a href=\"https://playgroundai.com/\">Playground AI</a></p></li><li><p><a href=\"https://www.midjourney.com/\">Midjourney</a></p></li></ul><p>The text of the adventures and music are Copyright © 2023 by Bruce Kvam. Permission is granted for personal use, not redistribution.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":118750,"name":"DM Notes","type":"text","_id":"7Hg5FH7pHR3YmPAL","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>This setting is intended for experienced D&amp;D 5th edition characters (starting at fifth level). These adventures can be dropped into an existing campaign where existing fifth-level characters are recruited into the squad, or you can create new characters at fifth level, or you can use the @UUID[.6whwN2ZZudLhtTxx]{sample characters.}</p><img src=\"modules/flying-squad/images/flying-squad-street.webp\" /><p><em>The Flying Squad name was inspired by the London police unit started in the 1920s.</em></p><p><strong>Note:</strong> to show images that appear in the journal (like the one above) to the players:</p><ul><li><p>Click the image.</p></li><li><p>A separate window will open.</p></li><li><p>Click the Show Players button in the title bar of the window.</p></li></ul><h2>Location</h2><p class=\"western\">Adventures will take place in and around the city; there will be no long-distance travel.</p><p class=\"western\">This means that players can come and go each week without having to worry about their characters having to travel 200 miles to catch up with the rest of the squad. The @UUID[Item.yv2YbVDxIIo7x4CS]{Amulet of Sending}<span style=\"font-style:normal\"> each investigator is provided with allows easy communication between party members, and the @UUID[Item.5aMlGUpGX3h0Xlc1]{Cloak of Flight} can quickly reunite them.</span></p><p class=\"western\">The exact city is left open to allow you to place the flying squad in any campaign. Waterdeep makes a good base of operations, but any large city in any world will do. Preferably it will be on the ocean near a large river.</p><h2>DMing Investigations</h2><p>The first rule is to have fun.</p><p><strong>Don't be stingy with clues. </strong>There should always be multiple clues that lead the squad to the suspect. If the players somehow miss them, use an NPC to point something out, or have Mindy, the Flying Squad's office manager, show up with the necessary information.</p><p><strong>Passive Checks:</strong> Having the players constantly rolling Perception and Investigation rolls can be immersion breaking. Instead, consider using passive Perception and Investigation checks for run-of-the mill checks. The passive value for each skill is listed in parentheses on the character sheet after the modifier.</p><p>The total for a passive check is:</p><p style=\"text-align:center\">10 + all modifiers that normally apply</p><p>For a 5th level character with Wisdom 14 and proficiency in Perception, this would be:</p><p style=\"text-align:center\">15 = 10 + 3 (proficiency bonus) + 2 (Wisdom bonus)</p><p>When a character's passive total exceeds the DC of the clue, just tell the player what they find.</p><p><strong>Keep the Ball Rolling:</strong> If you need to, fudge Perception and Investigation rolls.</p><p><strong>Let the Players Win:</strong> If the players have a good idea that isn't mentioned in these case notes, or you didn't think of, let them run with it.</p><p><strong>Kill or Capture: </strong>Some suspects are humanoid and should be captured and face justice in the court system, rather than killed outright. Some suspects are evil monsters and should be destroyed. In either case, full XP for defeating the creature should be awarded.</p><p>When a creature is reduced to 0 hit points <strong>by a melee attack</strong> the player can decide at that moment whether to knock the target out or kill them. See @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.rules.6PfYpwxkdQkyS6b7.JournalEntryPage.ckTc3L0Byh2WMHsp#knocking-a-creature-out]{Knocking a Creature Out} in the D&amp;D rules under @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.rules.6PfYpwxkdQkyS6b7.JournalEntryPage.njF9PueE9rmnn8N8]{The Order of Combat}. Note that ranged and spell damage cannot be mitigated this way.</p><p><strong>NPC Deaths: </strong>The squad's goal is to bring criminals to justice, rather than kill them. Therefore, when named humanoid NPCs are reduced to 0 hit points treat them as characters, giving them death saving throws each round until they stabilize or die. You many wish to do the same with some named monsters.</p><h2>Backup</h2><p>@UUID[Actor.r8BUf0tfWy6fAxqR]{Mindy} is the office manager, and as a half-elf is on duty 20 hours a day. The squad can call her for backup or @UUID[Actor.OdcDE5pocdHhPknm]{Broam Larkspur} pretty much any time with an @UUID[Item.yv2YbVDxIIo7x4CS]{Amulet of Sending} should they get in over their heads. Officers of the law aren't totally on their own and have every expectation that their fellow officers will help them out of a jam. However, if this happens too frequently the captain will begin to question their competence. . . .</p><p>Keep a couple of the Example PCs around the office as backup to rescue the player characters if they send an SOS.</p><h2>First Case</h2><p>The first case for the squad is @UUID[JournalEntry.74x8sFNKT2zFyQ5S]{The Case of the Butchered Butcher} (@UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.vNnty834hnP1LnFm]{import} if the link is broken)<em>. </em>This murder leads to a linked series of cases, which can be installed from the Flying Squad Adventure compendium as needed.</p><p><strong>Technical Questions: </strong>If you have a question about how something works or something is missing, see @UUID[.90ZqYF7BDh9QAjkO]{Technical Notes}.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":0},"flags":{}},{"sort":125000,"name":"Character Backgrounds","type":"text","_id":"znMKpMdpJSnmgHWX","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>All the standard D&amp;D 5e backgrounds are available, but the following law-enforcement related backgrounds can be chosen to provide the requisite skill proficiencies.</p><p>@UUID[Item.TfzlrP7Fkz1qCGe5]{Artist}</p><p>@UUID[Item.K6eBNGphhSvyjfVv]{Bounty Hunter}</p><p>@UUID[Item.NnM1lONBMrN96n20]{City Watch}</p><p>@UUID[Item.EswWVWCpBxx5xRKG]{Informant}</p><p>@UUID[Item.zDQHxdyJfNkdWdQt]{Locksmith}</p><p>@UUID[Item.FOW5j9yLze1oSwYm]{Merchant}</p><p>@UUID[Item.HG2DsY4WlP5GCJD6]{Private Investigator}</p><p></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":112500,"name":"Introduction","type":"text","_id":"AGKvoWfiD5DPYxK3","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>You are walking down a street when you see a notice posted on a wall:</p><div style=\"font-size:16pt\"><p style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"font-family:Modesto Condensed\">WANTED:</span></p><p style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"font-family:Modesto Condensed\">WIZARDS, WARLOCKS, SORCERERS, CLERICS, DRUIDS, <br />MONKS, BARDS, PALADINS, FIGHTERS, RANGERS<br />and, lamentably, ROGUES of <strong>impeccable</strong> character <br />to assist the city watch in the investigation of crimes</span></p><p style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"font-family:Modesto Condensed\">Apply to Capt. Larkspur at the Palace</span></p><p style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"font-family:Modesto Condensed\">NO BARBARIANS NEED APPLY!</span></p></div><p class=\"western\">Being at loose ends and in need of a career change, and considering yourself a person of <em>impeccable</em> character, you decide to apply to the City Watch.</p><p class=\"western\">After an intense interview and magical vetting by a paladin, you are inducted into the City Watch. After your initial training period you are assigned to an elite unit of the City Watch, the Flying Squad, formed to investigate crimes that have heretofore been unsolvable<em>.</em></p><p class=\"western\">Your squad will be assigned cases, frequently murders, that have stumped the regular City Watch patrols.</p><p class=\"western\">You have jurisdiction across the entire city, rather than being assigned to a specific ward or precinct.</p><p class=\"western\">And yes, the Flying Squad can actually fly with their @UUID[Item.5aMlGUpGX3h0Xlc1]{Cloaks of Flight}.</p><img src=\"modules/flying-squad/images/flying-squad1.jpg\" class=\" centered\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" />","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":121875,"name":"Background Information","type":"text","_id":"8q8xsYh9tGeWefJ7","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>There has been a rash of murders in which the victims’ hearts and tongues (or heads) have been removed, making successful casting of <em>raise dead</em> and <em>speak with dead</em> spells impossible, and drastically increasing the difficulty of solving these crimes.</p><p>The head of the City Watch commissioned the construction of a special item, the @UUID[Item.1BzXP6tRiZpoEGLP]{Crown of Communing}, to circumvent these limitations, and formed a special unit, the Flying Squad, to use it.</p><p class=\"western\">Because of their special duties, these investigators may come from a wider variety of backgrounds than regular members of the Watch.</p><p>An allied organization, the @UUID[JournalEntry.HkUyKycM2w2ODySP]{Temple of Truth and Justice}, can provide clerical services should the need arise.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":123438,"name":"Character Creation","type":"text","_id":"rg0dy2ax42hIuO33","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<ul><li><p class=\"initial\">You can be any character class and race except barbarian.</p></li><li><p class=\"western\">You will start at level 5 (6,500 experience points).</p></li><li><p class=\"western\">You can choose any non-chaotic, non-evil alignment (NG, LG, N, or LN).</p></li><li><p class=\"western\">You must have a class or background skill proficiency in at least one of the following: Insight, Intimidation, Investigation, Perception or Survival (for tracking).</p></li><li><p class=\"western\">There should be at least one cleric and one wizard character in the group, to have your magical bases covered, and to use the <em>@UUID[Item.1BzXP6tRiZpoEGLP]{crown of communing}</em>.</p></li></ul><h1>Rank and Responsibilities</h1><p class=\"western\">One of your characters will be the ostensible leader of your squad, and will assume the rank of @UUID[Item.Xc4xCD1NF7LNm1kn]{lieutenant} in the City Watch. The lieutenant must have Charisma or Wisdom of 14 or higher.</p><p class=\"western\">The others will hold the rank of @UUID[Item.HQD6BYU1qoyXRm30]{constable} or @UUID[Item.VlMDvH8cQ9ZXHx4E]{sergeant}, at your choice. A sergeant must have Charisma or Wisdom of 12 or higher, and a constable 10 or higher.</p><p>Your squad's commanding officer has his office at the palace, and his rank is captain (Charisma or Wisdom of 16 or higher required).</p><p>Officers who display leadership and bravery may win promotions, though service of at least two years in a rank is usually required before a promotion is granted.</p><p>You wear your insignia of rank on your cloak.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><img src=\"modules/flying-squad/images/objects/constable.jpg\" alt=\"Constable\" width=\"128\" height=\"128\" /></td><td><img src=\"modules/flying-squad/images/objects/sergeant.jpg\" alt=\"Sergeant\" width=\"128\" height=\"128\" /></td><td><img src=\"modules/flying-squad/images/objects/lieutenant.jpg\" alt=\"Lieutenant\" width=\"128\" height=\"128\" /></td><td><img src=\"modules/flying-squad/images/objects/captain.jpg\" alt=\"Lieutenant\" width=\"128\" height=\"128\" /></td></tr><tr><td>@UUID[Item.HQD6BYU1qoyXRm30]{Constable}</td><td>@UUID[Item.VlMDvH8cQ9ZXHx4E]{Sergeant}</td><td>@UUID[Item.Xc4xCD1NF7LNm1kn]{Lieutenant}</td><td>@UUID[Item.XK2C1Ka5Ps09eIYB]{Captain}</td></tr></tbody></table><p class=\"western\">One character (a spellcaster) must become attuned with the @UUID[Item.1BzXP6tRiZpoEGLP]{Crown of Communing}.</p><h1>Hooks, Bonds, Flaws</h1><p class=\"western\">From the lists below, pick one or more positive character hooks (taken as a bond), each balanced by one negative character hook (taken as a flaw). You can also make up your own hooks. Provide names and brief descriptions of any people mentioned. You should avoid choosing the same hook as another player.</p><h2>Positive Character Hooks</h2><ul><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">A relative or friend runs a shop in the market.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">A relative or friend is in the city’s army.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">A relative or friend is in the City Watch.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">You are related to a noble family.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">You are an orphan and were adopted by a wealthy merchant.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">You have a well-known reputation as a celebrated member of your class.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">People constantly mistake you for a member of the nobility and want to be your <em>friend</em>.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">People just like to talk to you.</p></li></ul><h2>Flaws</h2><ul><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">You are prone to alcoholic blackouts.</p></li></ul><ul><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">A half-brother or -sister is a wanted criminal; your relationship is unknown to the authorities.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">You are having a secret affair with the spouse of an important city official.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">Your family has a secret history of dragon/demon/outsider worship.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">You are universally disliked by an entire class of merchants, or thieves, traders, blacksmiths, woodworkers, tavern keepers, etc.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">You have made an enemy of an important person in the city.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">People always pick fights with you.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">People constantly mistake you for someone else (a criminal, vagabond or con man) and want to beat you to a bloody pulp.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">People are always giving you the cold shoulder.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">Dead bodies creep you out.</p></li></ul><p class=\"western\"></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":162500,"name":"Equipment","type":"text","_id":"9tE5w7BIco1y6Iax","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p class=\"initial\">The City Watch will provide each investigator with the following:</p><ul><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">Your choice of nonmagical armor and weapons. The @UUID[Actor.4raWazhWJ6TABJBp]{Weapons Rack} in the Evidence Room of the station has all these items, and you can open its character sheet and drag items from its inventory into your character sheet's inventory.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">Any equipment or materials required for your investigations.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">Flying Squad uniform: black tunic and a @UUID[Item.5aMlGUpGX3h0Xlc1]{Cloak of Flight}, with faint silver wings on the back.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\"><span style=\"text-decoration:none\"><em>@UUID[Item.yv2YbVDxIIo7x4CS]{Amulet of Sending}. <strong>Note: </strong>This device can be very useful to call backup from the station if the squad gets in over their heads.</em></span></p></li><li><p>The station has one set of @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.items.wGKykLRS8UqChNXI]{Dimensional Shackles} in the evidence locker, used for preventing creatures from teleporting away.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">Monthly salaries. Constable: 100 gp, Sergeant: 120 gp, Lieutenant: 150 gp, Captain: 200 gp. This salary can be collected at the Bursar's office in the @UUID[JournalEntry.omHJShQ5LXmS7pU2]{courthouse}.</p></li><li><p class=\"bullet-entry\">Most of your assignments will take place in the city, so there won’t be a need for field rations, camping gear, etc.</p></li></ul><p class=\"western\">One of you will be entrusted with a @UUID[Item.1BzXP6tRiZpoEGLP]{Crown of Communing}, which you must protect with your very life.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":181250,"name":"Experience Awards","type":"text","_id":"PWCWHSeV8BGW9S3P","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>If your characters gain levels with experience points, experience can be gained from using your deductive powers in addition to capturing perpetrators and putting them in jail (and defeating foes, of course).</p><p><strong>Investigation XP:</strong> Experience can be gained by performing investigations, taking a suspect to trial, or basically, for thinking to check for something that provides a substantial clue. This is generally equal to the experience gained by defeating a creature whose Challenge Rating is your current level.</p><p>For example, if you think to interview the old lady who's always watching the street from her flat over the crime scene and she can describe the perpetrator, the squad will immediately gain 1,800 XP. If it's a dead-end, there's no extra XP award.</p><p><strong>Deduction XP: </strong>If you make a correct deduction based on the clues you've found, state your deduction to the GM and record it in your player notes. The deductions need to be substantial: identifying a perpetrator, for example.</p><p>At the end of the case examine all your deductions. For all correct deductions you will receive XP for the CR equal to your current level. For example, if at level 6 you make the correct deduction \"It was Professor Plum with the rolling pin in the kitchen,\" you will receive 2,300 XP. If the deduction is incorrect it may provide a good laugh.</p><p><strong>Rescue XP:</strong> You also receive XP for rescuing kidnaping victims, people getting mugged, etc.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":123000,"name":"Department Policies","type":"text","_id":"1PlkGNzNSSY9ySZ2","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>The following policies apply to the duties and conduct of Flying Squad officers.</p><p>The officer overseeing the squad's performance, Capt. Broam Larkspur, is a meticulous paladin and stickler for the rule of law and humane treatment of suspects.</p><h2>Civil Forfeiture</h2><p class=\"initial\">Evidence, assets and equipment used in the commission of a crime are subject to forfeiture by the squad. These items are to be kept in the armory of the squad’s office pending the outcome of criminal proceedings. If perpetrators are found guilty in a court of law the forfeiture is permanent.</p><p class=\"western\">These items can be used by the squad in pursuit of their duties. Cash and valuables seized from suspects apprehended in the commission of a crime are to be deposited in the strongbox in the armory. These funds may be used for squad expenses; for example, to pay for the casting of spells to raise innocent bystanders who were killed as collateral damage during the apprehension of suspects.</p><h2>Use of Force</h2><p class=\"initial\">Squad members should use non-lethal means in pursuit of suspects if possible.  See @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.rules.6PfYpwxkdQkyS6b7.JournalEntryPage.ckTc3L0Byh2WMHsp#knocking-a-creature-out]{Knocking a Creature Out} in the D&amp;D rules.</p><p class=\"initial\">Injury to bystanders and damage to civilian property should be avoided at all costs. See Unwritten Rule #1 below.</p><p class=\"western\">Medical and magical aid should be rendered to all injured humanoid suspects so that they may appear at trial.</p><h2>Use of Magic</h2><p class=\"initial\">Magic may not be used to coerce confessions from suspects. Spells such as <em>zone of truth</em><span style=\"font-style:normal\"> may be used to help determine the veracity of testimony.</span></p><p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-style:normal\">Spells such as </span><em>charm person</em><span style=\"font-style:normal\"> and </span><em>suggestion </em><span style=\"font-style:normal\">may be used to gain the trust and cooperation from suspects, but charmed suspects cannot be held liable for any statements made or actions performed while under the effects of any mind control magic.</span></p><p class=\"western\"><span style=\"font-style:normal\">Officers may be held liable for the conduct of those under their mental control.</span></p><h2>Testimony and Trials</h2><p>If a case goes to trial officers may need to testify at court. Most cases do not result in a trial, as criminals who admit their guilt under <em>zone of truth </em>usually do not protest their innocence and instead cooperate with the authorities, turning on their co-conspirators to reduce their sentences.</p><p>See the @UUID[JournalEntry.aGzVXFlfaccwEFmo]{The Trial of Madrigal Mott} @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.wDLjtQFtCbeu2arN]{import} for an example of how a trial might be conducted.</p><h2>Search Warrants</h2><p>Technically speaking, the officers must obtain a search warrant from a magistrate if they wish to search a home or place of business. This is roundly ignored by both the city watch and the courts, but see @UUID[.1PlkGNzNSSY9ySZ2#unwritten-rule-#1:-the-rich-are-different]{Unwritten Rule #1: The Rich Are Different}.</p><h2>Accountability</h2><p>Investigators may be subjected to <em>zone of truth</em> while testifying in court. Deviation from department policies can range from temporary suspension, reduction in rank, loss of pay, dismissal, and in severe cases, prosecution and imprisonment upon conviction.</p><h2>Raising the Dead</h2><p>Department policy is, put bluntly, to \"let dead dogs lie.\" Victims are generally not raised from the dead. Officers are not supposed to pick and choose who lives and who dies.</p><p>However, at the discretion of the lieutenant, department funds (from civil forfeiture) can be used to raise the dead if their testimony is essential to making a case, and no relatives can be found who can foot the bill.</p><h2>Bounties and Rewards</h2><p>Bounties and rewards are offered for the capture of some wanted criminals and return of missing persons. They are indicated on the @UUID[JournalEntry.d7LgQdmXcKDWDzix]{wanted posters and missing persons notifications}.</p><p>The funds for these are usually put up by the criminals' civilian victims, who hope to recover their stolen merchandise, or to provide an extra incentive to the City Watch for searching for their missing person.</p><p>As such, the members of the squad <strong>are eligible</strong> for the bounties and rewards. If the bounty is put up by the city, however, members of the City Watch are ineligible.</p><h1>Unwritten Rules</h1><p>The following rules are unofficial, passed from one squad member to another.</p><h2>Unwritten Rule #1: The Rich Are Different</h2><p>The Flying Squad exists because of the support of the wealthiest citizens in the city. Care must be taken whenever dealing with them and when operating in their neighborhoods. If a case involves the wealthy or nobles policies must be strictly adhered to, otherwise the charges may be thrown out of court due to police or prosecutorial misconduct.</p><h2>Unwritten Rule #2: I Got Your Back</h2><p>The squad never leaves an officer behind. If a fellow officer goes down the first order of business is to get them back on their feet. See Rule #3.</p><h2>Unwritten Rule #3: One for You and One for Me</h2><p>Always carry two potions of healing. One for your fellow officer and one for yourself.</p><h2>Unwritten Rule #4: We Found It, It's Ours!</h2><p>The official policy is that weapons, armor and treasure belonging to criminals is subject to civil forfeiture. Translation: We found it, it's ours! However, if officers get too grabby and take something from the wrong person (i.e., a rich one), they're heading to prison.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":171875,"name":"Magic Items and Spells","type":"text","_id":"Zbmvo9Picz4hD5ZH","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Magic Items</h2><p>The following magic items are available to the Flying Squad. These can be added to the character sheet by clicking the links below, dragging and dropping them on the character sheet.</p><p>To attune an item:</p><ul><li><p>Click the Inventory tab on the character sheet.</p></li><li><p>Click the Edit Item icon in the Inventory entry for the item you wish to attune</p></li><li><p>Click the Details tab</p></li><li><p>Click the Attunement dropdown and change it to Attuned</p></li></ul><p>@UUID[Item.yv2YbVDxIIo7x4CS]{Amulet of Sending}</p><p>@UUID[Item.5aMlGUpGX3h0Xlc1]{Cloak of Flight}</p><p>@UUID[Item.1BzXP6tRiZpoEGLP]{Crown of Communing}</p><p>If you're attuned to the crown also drag and drop these versions of he spells to your spell book:</p><ul><li><p>@UUID[Item.F0dxBkFmvg9xloNf]{Commune with Dead (Crown)}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Item.Jwa3sodtf4ppLk7G]{Deathvision (Crown)}</p></li><li><p>@UUID[Item.kSbcoAvB3l7ToZ2p]{Speak with Dead (Crown)}</p></li></ul><p>Then for each of the above spells:</p><ul><li><p>Select the Spellbook tab of the character sheet</p></li><li><p>Drag and drop the spell on the Spellbook</p></li><li><p>Click the Edit Item icon in the spell entry</p></li><li><p>Click the Details tab for the spell</p></li><li><p>Click the item select dropdown for the Resource (the dropdown after the \"Item Uses\" dropdown).</p></li><li><p>Select Crown of Communing</p></li></ul><p>@UUID[Item.FM7FTw0TT1f7aMut]{Xero's Magic Quill}</p><h2>New Spells</h2><p>The following new spells are available to clerics, wizards, sorcerers and warlocks. These can be dragged and dropped in your spellbook.</p><p>@UUID[Item.bRsvq6LxZtywzgLa]{Commune with Dead}</p><p>@UUID[Item.g4WU0PU7lupNKFFa]{Deathvision}</p><h2>Wizard Spells</h2><p>As part of their rigorous training for the Flying Squad wizards are taught the following defensive, infiltration, influencing, information, and crowd control spells, in addition to any they pick up on their own. These can be dragged and dropped in your spellbook.</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.eS7XnnApoxRxYXPs]{Charm Person}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.cg50KpBkBdPK6vPL]{Clairvoyance}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.ghXTfe7sgCbgf1Q8]{Detect Magic}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.ppWAAEul0QHtm4er]{Detect Thoughts}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.A3q2gTNqG6fvNGrv]{Disguise Self}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.XXUDGFELgoskdOD0]{Fear}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.CKZTpZlxj7hjjo2H]{Mage Armor}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.aU62xVUBYkAQWIHv]{Nondetection}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.XZhdgVK3cLoxNCQl]{Remove Curse}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.z1mx84ONwkXKUZd7]{Shield}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.KhwiSi9fwVfUPtku]{Sleep}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.DQzlB5Y3k791W5bH]{See Invisibility}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.TwlD4PLcltv7Xh7j]{Stinking Cloud}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.zMAWdyc8UVb37BK4]{Suggestion}</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":123048,"name":"The Station","type":"text","_id":"A3UpW4vrDHvnEnUa","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p class=\"initial\"><em>Activate the @UUID[Macro.nugFI6H5NCbHJZHU]{Flying Squad Station} scene in The Flying Squad folder of the Scenes tab.</em></p><p class=\"initial\">The Flying Squad station is not far from the palace, near fine eating and drinking establishments.</p><img src=\"modules/flying-squad/maps/station-100.webp\" /><h3 class=\"western\">1. Reception</h3><p class=\"initial\">This area has a desk for your receptionist, a half-elf constable named Mindy, and four chairs. There is a bulletin board near the door with various notices, wanted posters and a city map.</p><p>Mindy keeps the station in order, making sure that there are plenty of arrows in the armory, that the books in the library are properly shelved, that any prisoners are properly fed and secured, that Rendel has everything spic and span, etc.</p><p>If the members of the squad need anything, Mindy is always on call and can usually be reached with the <em>amulet of sending</em>. She will respond immediately, even if she is tranced.</p><p class=\"western\">The door is made of thick iron-bound wood and can be barred from the inside.</p><h3 class=\"western\">2. Bullpen</h3><p class=\"initial\">The bullpen for the sergeants and constables. There are six desks and chairs, with bookcases for each.</p><h3 class=\"western\">3. Lieutenant’s Office</h3><p class=\"initial\">This is the office of the lead inspector in charge of the Flying Squad.</p><p class=\"western\">There is a desk with a chair, a bookcase.</p><h3 class=\"western\">3a. Interrogation Room</h3><p class=\"western\">There is a table with four chairs around it. A pair of manacles is bolted to the table to control unruly suspects.</p><p class=\"western\">A barred window overlooks the street.</p><h3 class=\"western\">4. Library</h3><p class=\"initial\">Book cases line the walls of this room. There are two tables with four chairs each. A card catalog is near the door.</p><p class=\"western\">The library is stocked with all the standard works on arcane lore, history, law; most everything that a researcher would need to help solve a case.</p><p class=\"western\">A barred window overlooks the street.</p><h3 class=\"western\">5. Armory</h3><p class=\"initial\">This room is stocked with two of every nonmagical weapon. There is a barrel of arrows and a smaller one of crossbow bolts, which are replenished on a regular basis by Mindy.</p><p class=\"western\">The iron door of the armory is locked with <em>arcane lock</em>, with the password “swordfish.”</p><h3 class=\"western\">6. Holding Cells</h3><p class=\"initial\">There are four holding cells here for suspects who are brought in. Each cell has two cots, a sink and a chamber pot.</p><p class=\"western\">The cells are separated from each other by brick walls and from the holding cell entry area by bars. The cell doors are bars that swing open, and have an opening where food can be passed in and prisoners can extend their hands so they can be manacled before the cell door is opened.</p><p>The turnkey is Rendel. He feeds and waters any prisoners and cleans up around the station.</p><p class=\"western\">Prisoners are usually held here until transfer is arranged to the main city jail.</p><p class=\"western\">A locked cabinet holds 10 pairs of wrist manacles and 10 pairs of ankle manacles. Another cabinet holds water and simple rations for the prisoners.</p><p>Two sets of manacles are set in the north wall for times of overcrowding.</p><h3 class=\"western\">7. Lavatory</h3><p class=\"initial\">There is a sink and hand pump to wash up with.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":120313,"name":"Personalizing the Campaign","type":"text","_id":"cWXtTAKnLr7GuBmj","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>D&amp;D campaigns that directly engage the players are more fun than ones where the player characters are just on the outside looking in. A good way of doing this is giving the player character a stake in the world or some kind of connection to the non-player characters in the adventure.</p><p>Character backgrounds are a great place to make a more personal link to the campaign. For example:</p><ul><li><p>A half-orc has a friend or sister who is a member of the @UUID[JournalEntry.74x8sFNKT2zFyQ5S.JournalEntryPage.fYAan8m25SuYZs78#the-red-claws]{Red Claws} @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.vNnty834hnP1LnFm]{import}.</p></li><li><p>A bard has regularly performed at the infamous @UUID[JournalEntry.bMEVZLmHouwdVRM5]{Midnight Sun} @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.YaNdjeNE5RzC2czk]{import} tavern in the seediest part of town.</p></li><li><p>A female spellcaster had an affair with Abelard Mott, @UUID[JournalEntry.VbTJ2qMAUc8HmrLc]{a wealthy man who is found dead} @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.wDLjtQFtCbeu2arN]{import}. She is unexpectedly named the heir to his fortune. His estranged wife accuses her of seducing, charming and killing him!</p></li><li><p>A character with the City Watch background has a history with a dirty cop, Simeon Snag, who has made a deal with a gang posing as the \"City Wach\" in the seediest part of town in @UUID[JournalEntry.mqcL1f4oS9Y4Uq4s]{The Case of the Counterfeit Coppers} @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.1NitxYHNUyJhAXLq]{import}.</p></li><li><p>A character with the Private Investigator background learns that a suspect is a former client, for whom they did some less-than-totally honest work, which would be embarrassing if it came to light.</p></li><li><p>A character with the Bounty Hunter background realizes that a murder suspect they spent months trying to track down unsuccessfully is the same person they're chasing now.</p></li><li><p>If there's a character whose parents died tragically, they were actually murdered by @UUID[Actor.w0AEUrw7E5hcmwOE]{Crybaby} @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.PD0Ece26PAdcs3P6]{import}, an infamous assassin.</p></li></ul><p>If you are dropping these adventures into an existing campaign, you may wish to substitute the player characters' family or acquaintances of the player characters for the victims or perpetrators of the events herein.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":0},"flags":{}},{"sort":121094,"name":"Modifying Challenge Ratings","type":"text","_id":"UOJDDlcpspYDoeBt","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Depending on the order of the leads the players follow up on, you may need to increase or decrease the challenge rating of the NPC encounters. The easiest way is to increase or reduce the number of creatures in the encounters (add an extra ghoul or two to the ghoul encounter, increase the size of the gang at Snakhar's hideout in The Pits, add or subtract another thrall in the Eldritch House, and so forth).</p><h2>Increasing Challenge Ratings</h2><p>If the characters drastically outlevel the named NPCs (such as Findizier or Snakhar), increase their Challenge Rating. The guidelines in the Dungeon Master's Guide for calculating CR can be helpful, but here are some easy ways:</p><ul><li><p>Increase their AC, by adding better armor or a shield, increasing Dexterity by 2, etc.</p></li><li><p>Increase hit points, by changing them directly, or by increasing Constitution</p></li><li><p>Increase the damage of attacks by increasing Strength or a weapon that does more damage</p></li><li><p>Add higher-level spells for spellcasters</p></li><li><p>Add additional features (see below)</p></li><li><p>Replace them with a similar type of monster with an appropriately higher Challenge Rating.</p></li></ul><p>For example, Findizier starts out as a Vampire Spawn with the added Shapechanger feature, but if the squad doesn't meet her until they are level 9 or 10, she may have developed the Charm action and the Misty Escape and Spider Climb features (from the CR 13 @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.monsters.DDO9lDCDtNHkfShP]{Vampire}). To grant her these powers:</p><ul><li><p>Click the @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.monsters.DDO9lDCDtNHkfShP]{Vampire} link.</p></li><li><p>Click the Import button in the Vampire window header and close that window.</p></li><li><p>Find the Vampire in the Actor tab of the Journal and click to open that window.</p></li><li><p>Find Findizier in the Actor tab and click to open her window.</p></li><li><p>Drag and drop the desired actions from the Vampire Features tab to Findizier's Features tab.</p></li><li><p>Increase the Challenge Rating (CR) in the upper right corner of the Findizier's character sheet.</p></li></ul><p>Other monsters can be found in the \"Monsters (SRD)\" compendium under the Actor heading in the Compendium tab.</p><h2>Reducing Challenge Ratings</h2><p>To reduce the CR of an actor do one or more of the following:</p><ul><li><p>Decrease the Challenge Rating (CR) in the upper right corner of the NPC's character sheet. This will reduce the actor's to-hit.</p></li><li><p>Decrease Strength and Dexterity. This will reduce damage and potentially AC.</p></li><li><p>Decrease Hit Points: click the gear that appears when you mouse over the Hit Points field at the top of the NPC character sheet.</p></li><li><p>Remove Features such as Multiattack, spells of higher levels, etc.</p></li></ul>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":0},"flags":{}},{"sort":122853,"name":"Conducting Investigations","type":"text","_id":"mQA5HgZsnHgWqnpb","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>The squad has a number of tools for conducting investigations.</p><h1>Skills</h1><h2>Perception</h2><p>A Wisdom (Perception) check is made to notice things: drops of blood, secret doors, etc. Other skills are used to figure out what to do about those things. After noticing the blood spatter, Wisdom (Survival) would be used to follow the trail.</p><h2>Investigation</h2><p>The Intelligence (Investigation) skill is important to solving cases. It's the primary skill used to figure things out. Perception is used to find things, but Investigation is used to figure out what those things mean.</p><p>When presented with clues, officers make Intelligence (Investigation) checks. If another officer uses the Help action to assist the character making the check, it is made at <strong>advantage</strong>.</p><p>In some cases, all the officers will make an Investigation check and the average will be used. For example, if all members of the squad fan out in an area of several city blocks to search for a suspect or clues, use the average of all their rolls.</p><h2>Survival</h2><p>The Wisdom (Survival) skill can be used to track suspects, but this is extremely difficult in the city environment unless they are dripping blood, have stepped in water or mud, etc.</p><p>In a crowded city an Intelligence (Investigation) check can frequently be substituted, by looking for other clues, questioning bystanders, etc.</p><h2>Insight</h2><p>When questioning a suspect a contest of the officer's Wisdom (Insight) against the suspect's Charisma (Deception) is made to determine the veracity of statements.</p><h2>Intimidation and Persuasion</h2><p>When questioning a suspect a contest of the officer's Charisma (Intimidation or Persuasion) is made against the higher of the suspect's Wisdom (Insight) or Charisma to determine whether the suspect is cowed or convinced by the threat or persuasion.</p><h1>Magic</h1><p>Various types of magic can be used to solve cases.</p><h2>Speaking with the Dead</h2><p>The @UUID[Item.1BzXP6tRiZpoEGLP]{Crown of Communing} can be used to speak with the dead, as can the <em>speak with dead</em> spell. These are limited, however, by the knowledge of the deceased. They don't always know what killed, and sometimes they don't want to talk to the authorities.</p><p>Second-hand testimony of the dead may not be used in court, nor can corpses be presented as evidence and questioned with spells before the magistrate.</p><h2>Enchantments: Charm, Suggestion</h2><p>These spells can be used to gain the cooperation of suspects and witnesses, but anything said or done while under their influence cannot be used in a court of law. Officers can be held liable for actions taken by those under their control, so these spells should be used very carefully.</p><h2>Zone of Truth</h2><p>The <em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.CylBa7jR8DSbo8Z3]{zone of truth}</em> spell can be used safely, for it does not compel behavior, it only allows the caster to determine the veracity of a statement, or that the caster failed to affect someone in its area of effect.</p><h2>Duplicating Documents</h2><p>The station has @UUID[Item.FM7FTw0TT1f7aMut]{Xero's Magic Quill}, which can be used to make copies of documents, portraits of suspects, etc., to show to witnesses.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":121485,"name":"Technical Notes","type":"text","_id":"90ZqYF7BDh9QAjkO","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Journal Macros</h2><p>To reduce the amount of digging around in the sidebar you'll have to do, the journal contains many links to scene changes, starting and stopping audio, importing adventures, rolling dice, executing macros, etc. They look like this:</p><ul><li><p>Play audio: @UUID[Playlist.DIl54fmwAhB7uEV4]{Play Fighting Music}</p></li><li><p>Stopping audio: @UUID[Macro.0Wccu78zaSXhQmSb]{Stop Music}</p></li><li><p>View a scene: @UUID[Macro.eIdHNuMaoMGtLWum]{Temple of Truth and Justice Scene}</p></li><li><p>Import an adventure: @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.vNnty834hnP1LnFm]{The Case of the Butchered Butcher}.</p></li><li><p>Display an actor: @UUID[Actor.OdcDE5pocdHhPknm]{Capt. Broam Larkspur}</p></li><li><p>Display an item: @UUID[Item.5aMlGUpGX3h0Xlc1]{Cloak of Flight}</p></li><li><p>Reference a rule: @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.rules.6PfYpwxkdQkyS6b7.JournalEntryPage.ckTc3L0Byh2WMHsp]{Damage and Healing}</p></li><li><p>Roll d20 with advantage: [[/r 2d20kh#d20 with advantage]]</p></li><li><p>Roll treasure: The ghoul has [[/r 2d6#Ghoul treasure]] gp.</p></li></ul><p>To use these macros just click them.</p><h2>Notes Display</h2><p>Links to journal entry descriptions of the scenes are available in scenes, allowing you to double-click a book icon to open the Journal entry for the scene. By default these notes are only displayed in Journal Notes mode.</p><p>To see these Notes Display icons at all times Notes Display must be toggled on:</p><ul><li><p>Click the Journal Notes button on the left side of the Foundry window.</p></li><li><p>Click the Toggle Notes Display button (the magnifying glass).</p></li><li><p>Click Token Controls button to exit Journal Notes mode.</p></li></ul><p>The Journal Notes will display as white book icons.</p><h2>Token Configuration</h2><p>Tokens have been configured to display name and hit points on hover, and most have been scaled to 0.8 so that they fit within the walls of a five-foot wide corridor without overlap. There are personal preferences, and yours may differ.</p><p>If you wish to change this, the most efficient way is to with Mass Edit module. If you don't have that module installed, here's how to get it.</p><ul><li><p>Click the Game Settings tab in the right sidebar.</p></li><li><p>Select Return to Setup.</p></li><li><p>Click Add-on Modules</p></li><li><p>Click Install Module at the bottom of the window.</p></li><li><p>Enter <strong>Mass Edit</strong> in the Filter Packages field.</p></li><li><p>Click the Install button at the bottom of the Install Module window.</p></li><li><p>Return to this world.</p></li><li><p>Click Game Settings.</p></li><li><p>Click Manage Modules.</p></li><li><p>Click the checkbox for Mass Edit.</p></li><li><p>Click Save Module Settings.</p></li></ul><p>To change the settings for all tokens in a scene:</p><ul><li><p>Press Ctrl+A to select all tokens.</p></li><li><p>Press Shift+E.</p></li><li><p>Make whatever changes you'd like in the Mass-Token EDIT dialog.</p></li><li><p>Click the Apply and Update Proto button.</p></li></ul><h2>Lighting</h2><p>Many scenes have global illumination turned on. These are for outdoor scenes or indoor scenes with artificial lighting.</p><p>If you're playing a scene at night you can turn down the brightness to set the mood:</p><ul><li><p>Click the Lighting Controls button at the left side of the window (the light bulb icon).</p></li><li><p>Click the Transition to Darkness button (the crescent moon icon).</p></li><li><p>Click the Token Controls button to get out of Lighting Control mode.</p></li></ul><p>Some scenes have lamps and the global illumination setting won't affect them.</p><p>To permanently disable the global illumination in a scene:</p><ul><li><p>Right-click the scene in the Scenes tab.</p></li><li><p>Click Configure in the dropdown menu.</p></li><li><p>Click the Lighting tab at the top of the Configure Scene window.</p></li><li><p>Uncheck the Global Illumination checkbox.</p></li><li><p>Click Save Changes.</p></li></ul><h2>Special Effects</h2><p>Some scenes have special effects that require you to switch out of Token Control mode to the Tile Controls to make a tile visible, or to toggle invisibility on a token such as a treasure chest or a hidden monster, or turn off a light.</p><h3>Turning off Lights</h3><ul><li><p>Click the Lighting Controls button (the light bulb) on the left side of the Foundry window. Light bulbs will appear on the canvas.</p></li><li><p>Double-click the light you want to turn off.</p></li><li><p>Right-click the light bulb.</p></li><li><p>Click the Token Controls button to get out of Lighting Control mode.</p></li></ul><p>Turning the light back on uses the same steps.</p><h3>Setting Tile Visibility</h3><p>To make a tile appear or disappear:</p><ul><li><p>Click the Tile Controls button on the left side of the window (the stack of blocks)</p></li><li><p>Hover the mouse cursor over the tile. Pressing the Alt key will outline all the tiles on the canvas, making it easier to find them.</p></li><li><p>Left-click the tile. The highlight will change color.</p></li><li><p>Right-click the tile. Control icons will appear around the tile.</p></li><li><p>Click the Toggle Visibility State icon (usually on the upper right). Some modules will change the location and appearance of this icon, so exact details may differ.</p></li><li><p>Click the Token Controls button to exit Tile Control mode.</p></li></ul><p>If you're using a module such as Monk's Active Tile Triggers you may want to set the tile up to become visible when clicked by the GM.</p><h3>Setting Token Visibility</h3><p>Some tokens, often monsters or treasure that the players haven't detected yet, are placed on the canvas in the invisible state.</p><p>To make them visible:</p><ul><li><p>Right-click the token.</p></li><li><p>Icons will appear around the token.</p></li><li><p>Click the Toggle Visibility State icon (usually on the upper right). Some modules will change the location and appearance of this icon, so exact details may differ.</p></li></ul><h2>Polymorphing</h2><p>Several NPCs and monsters can polymorph. If you wish to use this effect:</p><ul><li><p>Open the character sheet of the actor to be polymorphed by double-clicking the token on the canvas.</p></li><li><p>Find the new form in the Actors tab.</p></li><li><p>Click and drag the new form on to the character sheet of the actor that is changing shape.</p></li><li><p>To just change the token's appearance click the <strong>Appearance Only</strong> button. To do a true polymorph click the <strong>Polymorph</strong> button.</p></li><li><p>To revert the token back to the original appearance double-click the polymorphed token and click Restore Transformation in the character sheet title bar.</p></li></ul><h2>Treasure Tokens</h2><p>In some instances a token will be a chest or other object that has treasure inside it. See @UUID[.PmQqTCgUt3GEnGES]{Treasure Tokens}.</p><h2>Installing Adventures/Broken Links</h2><p>If you have not installed an adventure you may see broken links to entries in the Journal or the Actors tab that look like this: @UUID[JournalEntry.Ys1UyX3nOUvTpK]{Broken Link}. This most likely means that the adventure associated with the resource has not been imported yet, or it has been deleted.</p><p>If this happens:</p><ul><li><p>Go to the Compendium Packs tab of the right sidebar, or click the missing case in the list below.</p></li><li><p>Find the Flying Squad Adventure folder in the Compendium list. It may be in the Adventure or Default section.</p></li><li><p>Click the Flying Squad Adventure compendium. The compendium window will open.</p></li><li><p>Click the case that has the broken link and a window describing the case will open.</p></li><li><p>Click the Import Adventure at the bottom of the window.</p></li></ul><p>In many cases an \"import\" link is provided to the adventure and you can just click that.</p><p><strong>Note:</strong> If you reimport a case any changes you may have made to an actor, a scene or a journal entry <em>will be overwritten and lost</em>. If you change any of the installed items, be sure to duplicate them and place them in your own folders.</p><h2>Deleting Cases</h2><p>If you or your players start to notice slow load times you may need to delete NPC actors, scenes and journal entries. This is generally safe to do because you can just reimport adventures (see above), but if you have made changes to a scene, by adding or deleting tokens, changing their hit points, editing journal entries, changing actor inventories, those changes will be lost.</p><p>To delete folders for scenes and actors:</p><ul><li><p>Open the Scenes or Actors tab in the sidebar.</p></li><li><p>Right-click the folder you want to delete.</p></li><li><p>Select Delete All from the dropdown menu, or Delete to delete a single actor or scene.</p></li></ul><p>If your players use the example characters, be sure to duplicate those characters and place them in a Player Characters folder that you create where they won't be overwritten.</p><h2>Shortcuts to Case Compendium Entries</h2><p>Click the links below to import cases.</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.vNnty834hnP1LnFm]{The Case of the Butchered Butcher}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.HA8g5aqpDsG1jArW]{The Case of the Wary Werewolf}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.YaNdjeNE5RzC2czk]{The Case of the Reluctant Robber}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.ymSHmq5UZJSc22Fg]{The Case of the Underhanded Undertaker}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.1NitxYHNUyJhAXLq]{The Case of the Counterfeit Coppers}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.PD0Ece26PAdcs3P6]{The Case of the Ambitious Assassins}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.ewAU6qFvfOEWt8Ce]{The Case of the Naughty Necromancer}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.wfrcaCsIR9P5ErNu]{The Case of the Voluptuous Vampire}</p><p>@UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.wDLjtQFtCbeu2arN]{The Case of the Bilious Billionaire}</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":0},"flags":{}},{"sort":121680,"name":"Relations with Other Departments","type":"text","_id":"38oyV7d8hn3jS7Lf","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Because the Flying Squad is called for cases that are deemed too difficult for the regular city watch, and because the squad gets better toys, they engender a certain degree of jealousy and resentment.</p><p>Envious members of the regular City Watch sometimes refer to members of the Flying Squad as spooks or spookies, because of their black uniforms, because they look like wraiths when they take flight, and because they frequently speak to the dead.</p><p><strong>Flying Squad =&gt; Firing Squad =&gt; Frying Squad:</strong> If the squad becomes too free with their use of spells such as <em>fireball</em>, setting crime scenes on fire, or regularly skewering suspects with quivers full of arrows, members of the regular city watch will may be heard referring to them as the \"firing squad\" or \"frying squad\" and making comments along the lines of, \"Oh, look, the firing squad is on the scene. We're all saved!\"</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":0},"flags":{}},{"sort":122951,"name":"Undercover Investigations","type":"text","_id":"gGAKOiuHzoCfSuAu","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>The squad is free to conduct undercover investigations out of uniform. When doing so they should keep their insignia of rank and <em>amulet of sending</em> hidden on their person, but they will have to give up the <em>cloak of flight</em> because it has such a distinct appearance.</p><p>Officers are free to lie about their identities, but they may not commit any crimes. They must also be careful to avoid entrapment. If a suspect commits a crime at the urging of an officer, they may have a good defense if they have committed no other crimes, and the officer may face discipline.</p><p>Going undercover is recommended when investigating corrupt public officials to avoid alerting them and giving them a chance to flee or interfere with the investigation.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":119532,"name":"Casebook: List of Adventures","type":"text","_id":"0W61U92EnB7E1DZI","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>The Flying Squad Casebook is a series of linked adventures that begin with the murder of a butcher. The order listed below is approximately the order you should play them, based on difficulty, but if your players follow different clues they might do them out of sequence, possibly requiring some @UUID[.UOJDDlcpspYDoeBt]{modifications in difficulty}.</p><p>These cases can be found in the Flying Squad Adventure compendium. They must be installed from the compendium before they can be clicked on here.</p><p><em>If the links below are broken it means that you should import the adventure from the Flying Squad Adventure Compendium.</em></p><p>@UUID[JournalEntry.74x8sFNKT2zFyQ5S]{The Case of the Butchered Butcher}: @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.vNnty834hnP1LnFm]{import}</p><p>@UUID[JournalEntry.W5aqYrWAOeZCB5HM]{The Case of the Ghastly Ghouls} (included with the above)</p><p>@UUID[JournalEntry.CXTaDIJ8s6vMY7XO]{The Case of the Wary Werewolf}: @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.HA8g5aqpDsG1jArW]{import}</p><p>@UUID[JournalEntry.Q43euCdisvNfbfwb]{The Case of the Underhanded Undertaker}: @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.ymSHmq5UZJSc22Fg]{import}</p><p>@UUID[JournalEntry.UvEel3Y7C033Iq2Z]{The Case of the Reluctant Robber}: @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.YaNdjeNE5RzC2czk]{import} (contains mature themes, though nothing explicit. An alternative adventure path is provided for the mature themes.)</p><p>@UUID[JournalEntry.mqcL1f4oS9Y4Uq4s]{The Case of the Counterfeit Coppers}: @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.1NitxYHNUyJhAXLq]{import}</p><p>@UUID[JournalEntry.BgAbFstBtlbahQaF]{The Case of the Naughty Necromancer}: @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.ewAU6qFvfOEWt8Ce]{import}</p><p>@UUID[JournalEntry.r8I96QUqyrC6APWw]{The Case of the Ambitious Assassins}: @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.PD0Ece26PAdcs3P6]{import}</p><p>@UUID[JournalEntry.v1pMlwbFDT6Pk3cQ]{The Case of the Voluptuous Vampire}: @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.wfrcaCsIR9P5ErNu]{import}</p><p>@UUID[JournalEntry.VbTJ2qMAUc8HmrLc]{The Case of the Bilious Billionaire}: @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.wDLjtQFtCbeu2arN]{import}</p><p>(With apologies to Erle Stanley Gardner)</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":0},"flags":{}},{"sort":121583,"name":"Treasure Tokens","type":"text","_id":"PmQqTCgUt3GEnGES","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>In many scenes a token, usually a treasure chest, is provided that contains coins and loot. There are modules available, such as Item Piles and Loot Sheet NPC 5e, that allow players to take that loot from the tokens directly.</p><p>These tokens are defined as player characters, because the default NPC character sheet in Foundry does not display gold.</p><p>To copy items from a treasure token to a player's character sheet without the use of modules:</p><ul><li><p>Double-click the treasure token.</p></li><li><p>Click the Inventory tab of the treasure's character sheet</p></li><li><p>Open the character sheet to receive the items.</p></li><li><p>Click and drag the items from the treasure inventory to the character sheet inventory.</p></li><li><p>To transfer gold, silver, etc., manually update the values in the treasure token and the character sheet.</p></li></ul><h1>Item Piles</h1><p>If you're using Item Piles this process is simpler. First you need to enable the Item Piles module in the Manage Modules window.</p><p>Then, to turn a token into an Item Pile:</p><ul><li><p>Double click the treasure token to open the character sheet.</p></li><li><p>In the title bar of the window click Configure (with the open box icon for Item Piles). This may also be labeled Item Pile or Configure Pile, depending on the version of the module you have installed.</p></li><li><p>Click the Enabled checkbox.</p></li><li><p>Click the Update Item Pile button.</p></li></ul><p>Players should now be able to interact with the item pile token.</p><h1>Loot Sheet NPC 5e</h1><p>As of this writing, this module does not work with Foundry V11, but that may change.</p><p>To turn a treasure token into a Loot Sheet NPC:</p><ul><li><p>Left-click the token to select it.</p></li><li><p>Execute the ToggleType macro in the Flying Squad folder of the Macros Directory. Or just click this link: @UUID[Macro.hcLoWqyVnHDjRnwZ]{ToggleType}. You can also drag this link to the macro bar to make executing it easier.</p></li><li><p>Double-click the token to open its character sheet.</p></li><li><p>Click the Sheet configuration gear in the title bar of the window.</p></li><li><p>Change the sheet configuration in This Sheet to dnd5e.LootSheetNPC5e.</p></li><li><p>Click Save Sheet Configuration.</p></li><li><p>You may also need to change the actor's Configuration to grant players Observer access.</p></li></ul><p>The character sheet for the token will change to the loot sheet and players should be able to interact with it.</p><p>Note that this process may not be reversible — once converted to a Loot Sheet NPC a token will not change back to a player character sheet.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":0},"flags":{}},{"sort":121290,"name":"Other Modules","type":"text","_id":"Qa12AZUTud84uumO","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h1>Item Piles</h1><p>We recommend the most recent version of the Item Piles module for use with Flying Squad. Only a few clicks are required to convert the treasure and dead NPC tokens so that the players can take the coins and items directly without DM intervention. It's very convenient.</p><p>See @UUID[.PmQqTCgUt3GEnGES#item-piles]{Item Piles}.</p><h1>Monk's Little Details/Bloodsplats</h1><p>Many of NPCs in these adventures start out dead (this is a murder mystery, after all), but by default the Show Bloodsplat of this module option hides the tokens, preventing the players from seeing the tokens and potentially missing out on clues. </p><p>To see the tokens:</p><ul><li><p>Click the Configure Settings button in the Game Settings tab of the right sidebar.</p></li><li><p>Scroll down to the Monk's Little Details section on the left side of the Configure Game Settings wind and click it.</p></li><li><p>Scroll down the settings on the right side of the window until the Show Bloodsplat setting appears.</p></li><li><p>To turn off bloodsplats completely select No bloodsplats.</p></li><li><p>To show bloodsplats but don't hide the tokens, select Use bloodsplats, show tokens and set the Bloodsplat Opacity to a higher value (1 displays dead tokens completely).</p></li></ul><p>If you're using Monk's Bloodsplats the settings are similar.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":0},"flags":{}}],"folder":"t4OYJx9NxJtOfun3","sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":2,"dBogmx4vpeLG8Oap":3,"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6":3},"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.2.2","coreVersion":"10.303","createdTime":1682107582780,"modifiedTime":1691035273331,"lastModifiedBy":"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6"},"_id":"WT36xTPIdYhmg2hD"}
