{"folder":"t4OYJx9NxJtOfun3","name":"Courthouse","pages":[{"sort":-100000,"name":"Plan","type":"text","_id":"Msnw4ltuSZfFeWm3","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><em>Activate the @UUID[Macro.WbEcc5Zdxl6L8Kq3]{Courthouse} scene in The Flying Squad folder of the scenes tab.</em></p><p>Both criminal and civil trials are held in these courtrooms.</p><h1>A. Guardpost</h1><p>Four guards are on duty here, two by the street and two by the door.</p><h1>1. Reception</h1><p>Two guards are on duty here, on either side of the bursar's door.</p><h1>2. Records Office</h1><p>Records of births, deaths, property transfers, taxes, criminal and civil trials, registration of wills, etc., are all stored here. Officers can either request the registrar to conduct a search of the records, or they can make their own Intelligence (Investigation) check to look something up.</p><h1>3. Bursar's Office</h1><p>A guard is on duty here by the door in the northwest corner. People come and go all the time: shopkeepers and property owners pay their taxes, minor lawbreakers pay fines and city employees collect their salaries.</p><p>The doors in the office are very tough metal doors that are <em>arcane locked</em>. They require a DC 30 Strength check to break down and are DC 30 to pick with thieves tools.</p><p><strong>Exchange Services:</strong> The bursar can also exchange currencies, and buy gemstones and jewelry (which are usually placed in the mint). The bursar has a special magic item, the @UUID[Item.PT0nsQPcqc5beRDy]{Scales of Truth}, which in combination with a set of magical weights, give the true value of any item placed upon it, preventing the bursar from being defrauded.</p><p>The bursar can be converted to a merchant with your favorite merchant/loot module (Item Piles, for another) to provide the officers a place to exchange gems and jewelry obtained through civil forfeiture for the cash necessary to conduct squad duties, such as raising dead witnesses, removing curses, restoring them from petrification, etc.</p><h1>4. Vault</h1><p>The bursar sits at the desk behind the barred window.</p><p>The taxes and fines collected are in chests behind <em>arcane locked</em> metal doors. The doors are <em>arcane locked </em>once a week with new passphrases. They require a DC 30 Strength check to break down or pick with thieves' tools.</p><h1>5. Courtroom 1</h1><p>The magistrate sits at a high bench at the front of the courtroom, with a gallery at the back.</p><h2>a. Witnesses</h2><p>Witnesses waiting to testify are seated here. A low railing surrounds the witness's benches.</p><h2>b. Witness Box</h2><p>The testifying witness sits here.</p><h2>c. Magistrate's Bench</h2><p>The magistrate sits at a high bench.</p><h2>d. Court Reporter</h2><p>The court reporter sits here, taking shorthand notes. The evidence table is in the corner.</p><h2>e. Prisoner</h2><p>The prisoner is placed in a cage that is protected by a permanent antimagic shell to prevent spellcasters from escaping or wreaking other havoc</p><h2>f. Defense Table</h2><p>Advocates for the defense are seated here.</p><h2>g. Prosecutor's Table</h2><p>Advocates for the prosecution are seated here.</p><h2>h. Gallery</h2><p>Spectators are seated in the benches at the back of the courtroom. A low railing separates the gallery from the front of the courtroom.</p><p>The bailiff stands at attention beside the magistrate's bench. A guard is posted by the double doors during criminal trials.</p><h1>6. Courtroom 2</h1><p>A duplicate of courtroom 1.</p><h1>7. Holding Cells</h1><p>Defendants are held in these barred cells while they await arraignment or trial. Their advocates are allowed to speak with them in their cells, though little privacy is offered.</p><p>A guard is on duty as well.</p><h1>8-9. Magistrates' Offices</h1><p>The two main magistrates have offices here.</p><h1>10. Lavatory</h1><p>Clean water magically flows into the sinks from brass pipes when someone places their hands in the basin.</p><h1>11-14. Prosecutors' Offices</h1><p>The officers can make arrest and search warrant requests with the prosecutors in these offices.</p><h1>15. Evidence Locker</h1><p>Evidence submitted to the prosecution for trial is stored here. There is a lot of stuff here, packed away in chests stacked on shelves that are all numbered. The filing system is a little wonky; finding something is typically a DC 15 Intelligence (Investigation) check.</p><p>The locker is protected by a @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.64D1gNZ4hx7SWG2x]{Forbiddance} spell to prevent teleporting and gating into the room. Additionally, any elementals, fey, fiends or undead that enter will take 5d10 radiant damage when they enter and at the start of every turn they remain in the room.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":-200000,"name":"Introduction","type":"text","_id":"0CByBbNxnX39mTtB","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>When the squad testifies in court this courthouse is the venue. City records are also kept here, so any investigation of deeds, births, deaths, wills, etc., will take place in the @UUID[.Msnw4ltuSZfFeWm3#2.-records-office]{Records Office}.</p><p>Trials are decided by the magistrate after hearing evidence from counsel for the defense and prosecution. There are no juries.</p><h2>Search Warrants</h2><p>If the officers need to search a home or business, they can apply to a prosecutor for a search warrant, who will then ask a magistrate to approve it. This can take hours or days, depending on the reason and whose property is being searched.</p><h2>Arrest Warrants</h2><p>Officers can request arrest warrants for suspects who have escaped and for persons of interest. Wanted posters will be issued to all the watch stations in the city. The magistrates are more inclined to rule in favor of the prosecution in cases where arrest warrants are obtained and all the proper procedures have been followed before suspects are arrested, especially if their apprehension involves violence.</p><h2>Encounters</h2><p>If you need a random encounter to boost the characters' XP total, see @UUID[.GNeUCi0itsdf9NWg]{Courthouse Encounters}.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Courthouse Encounters","type":"text","_id":"GNeUCi0itsdf9NWg","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>The squad may visit the courthouse on occasion, to search city records, testify at trial, apply for a search or arrest warrant, collect their salaries, etc.</p><p>But wherever the squad goes, trouble follows. Here are four mini-adventures at the courthouse.</p><p>The links to the actors in the journal below can be dragged and dropped on the canvas to create the tokens that the characters can interact with.</p><p>Before running these encounters you may wish to duplicate the Courthouse scene to avoid changing the original:</p><ul><li><p>Click the Flying Squad folder of the Scenes tab.</p></li><li><p>Right-click the Courthouse scene.</p></li><li><p>Click Duplicate on the popup menu.</p></li><li><p>Right-click the Courthouse (Copy) scene.</p></li><li><p>Select Configure.</p></li><li><p>Change the Scene Name to reflect the officer's visit. Perhaps \"Prosecutor's Office,\" \"Arrest Warrant,\" \"Payday,\" etc.</p></li><li><p>Save the scene and make changes to it instead of the original Courthouse scene.</p></li></ul><h1>Robbing the Bursar</h1><p>A gang of robbers overpowers the guards, ties them up and tries to break into the vault to steal tax receipts and city payroll.</p><p><strong>Setup:</strong> Move all the guards in areas A, 1 and 3 into the Reception (area 1), and add the Restrained Status Effect to their tokens.</p><p>Drag and drop the following robbers into the Reception (area 1) and the Bursar's office (area 3):</p><ul><li><p>Three @UUID[Actor.APdQUTVQEKE5I8L3]{Bandits}</p></li><li><p>One @UUID[Actor.3LuzNs3pfhcwpFlx]{Bandit Captain}</p></li></ul><p>Drag and drop this Troll into the Bursar's office (area 3) by the door to the vault area, which it is trying to break down.</p><ul><li><p>One @UUID[Actor.SITi6FDlujIywmXY]{Troll}</p></li></ul><p><strong>The Encounter:</strong> When the squad approaches the front door of the courthouse they notice there are no guards on duty where they normally are. On a DC 12 Wisdom (Perception) check the officers notice blood on the cobbles near the door and on the door handle, as well as very large footprints in the grass.</p><p>The bandits are holding crossbows at the ready in area 1, while the bandit captain is shouting at the bursar in the vault area (4) to open the door.</p><p>The troll is trying to break down the door into the vault area, but it is <em>arcane locked</em>, requiring a DC 30 Strength check to break down. That means the troll can only succeed on a natural 20, since its Strength is only 18.</p><h1>Jailbreak</h1><p>A gang of thugs tries to break a buddy out of the holding cell while awaiting trial.</p><p><strong>Setup:</strong> Place the officers in area 14 of the courthouse.</p><p>Move the guards at area 7 and 7a into area 7b. Add the following villains into area 7:</p><ul><li><p>@UUID[Actor.ZQumiZE7uJgTJPcM]{Gang Leader}</p></li><li><p>Three @UUID[Actor.jnwVD8NuEksDHLQQ]{Gang Members}.</p></li><li><p>Place one @UUID[Actor.jnwVD8NuEksDHLQQ]{gang member}, who is awaiting trial, in an empty cell.</p></li></ul><p><strong>Encounter:</strong> The officers are in the office of the assistant prosecutor, Tanaquil, to get an arrest or search warrant. They hear shouting in the hall.</p><p>When the officers enter area 7 the gang leader has taken the holding cell keys from the guard and is unlocking the cell containing the gang member on trial.</p><h1>Burglary</h1><p>A gang of thieves tries to steal a magic item that has been placed in the evidence locker.</p><p><strong>Setup:</strong> Place the officers in area 13, Prosecutor Immerfroh's office.</p><p>Drag and drop the following actors into area 15, the Evidence Locker:</p><ul><li><p>@UUID[Actor.wW7NaiIFAoe6RcY3]{Mert}</p></li><li><p>Three @UUID[Actor.HHPlY7EANG0AllWK]{Thieves}</p></li></ul><p>Move the guard in 15 to the intersection of the corridors just south of the door to area 14.</p><p><strong>The Plot: </strong>The thieves have been hired to steal the Macalian Guffin, a bejeweled effigy of a bird that supposedly grants the bearer the ability to fly. It was captured by the City Watch from the lair of a master thief (@UUID[JournalEntry.d7LgQdmXcKDWDzix.JournalEntryPage.Ciw2OA06t4KicX9n]{Lavinia Shortbottom}) some years ago, but she escaped from jail and was never tried, so the recovered items have languished in the Evidence Locker.</p><p>The Locker is protected by the<span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"> @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.64D1gNZ4hx7SWG2x]{Forbiddance} spell</span>, preventing Mert from using his preferred method of burglary, <em>dimension door</em>. He has brought three gnome thieves along to expedite the search.</p><p>Mert picked the lock and cast <em>suggestion</em> on the guard, who got up and left. Mert's accomplices slammed the door and began the search for the Guffin.</p><p><strong>The Encounter:</strong> The squad is in the office of Prosecutor Immerfroh when they hear a man shout, \"Hey, how did you get in here?\" They hear a quieter, unintelligible intonation, and then they hear the first voice say, \"Yeah, I think I'll go for a long walk on a short pier. Thanks for the advice!\" Then a door slams and there are footfalls receding down the corridor.</p><p>All that happens in two rounds, catching the officers by surprise, leaving them little time to react. If they go into the hall immediately they see the guard from 15 at the T intersection to the south.</p><p>If they talk to the guard he explains that he is going down to the docks to take a long walk off a short pier. \"I haven't gone swimming in a long time, and my gnome friend thought today would be a great day for a dip in the ocean!\"</p><p>On a successful DC 14 Wisdom (Perception) check the squad hears the burglars ransacking the Evidence Locker for the Guffin. The lock is DC 20 to pick with thieves' tools and DC 22 to break down with a Strength check (rolled at <strong>advantage</strong> if two officers combine their strength). Or they can ask the guard for the key!</p><p>When the officers enter the room they find four gnomes furiously searching the chests on the shelves, wildly tossing items onto the floor. The <em>forbiddance</em> spell prevents entry by teleportation, but not exit. Mert tries to use <em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.A4RsPuSvB9wFtz1j]{dimension door}</em> to escape to the tree behind the courthouse, leaving his cohorts holding the bag.</p><p>A spellcaster can try to prevent Mert from leaving by casting <em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.Ek45cBpVXvJdv1Qy]{counterspell}</em> when he tries to <em>dimension door.</em> The thieves try to escape, fighting if they must, but when they lose half or more of their hit points they surrender.</p><p>If the officers have met Mert before (in @UUID[JournalEntry.mqcL1f4oS9Y4Uq4s]{The Case of the Counterfeit Coppers} @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.1NitxYHNUyJhAXLq]{import}) they should recognize him. The thieves have seen Mert around, but don't really know how to find him: he recruited them in the @UUID[JournalEntry.bMEVZLmHouwdVRM5]{Midnight Sun} @UUID[Compendium.flying-squad.fs-adventure.YaNdjeNE5RzC2czk]{import} tavern.</p><p>The Macalian Guffin is in fact in the evidence room, but it is, alas, not magical. It is worth 1,000 gp, however.</p><h1>Not Guilty!</h1><p>A villain that the squad had previously arrested kidnaps the grandchild of the magistrate to get exonerated!</p><p><strong>Setup: </strong>pick a particularly annoying villain that caused the squad a lot of trouble and put them in Area 1 with a @UUID[Actor.EjOGAtokxgbIkTX5]{barrister}.</p><p>Make the Coach with horse tile in front of the courthouse visible (click Tile Controls, click the coach tile and right click the tile and click the Toggle Visibility State icon).</p><p>Put a @UUID[Actor.dG4qzNOh1Njf4ZaY]{thug} in the driver's seat of the coach, and another @UUID[Actor.dG4qzNOh1Njf4ZaY]{thug} in the back of the coach with its Visibility State toggled. Finally, place a @UUID[Actor.yrUhjRxbVVuDWma6]{Child} with the second thug, with the Visibility state toggled.</p><p>If you want a tougher encounter, use a gang of the villain's original minions instead of the generic thugs.</p><p><strong>The Encounter:</strong> A criminal that the squad previously arrested walks out of the courthouse alongside a barrister as the squad approaches the front door of the courthouse. The criminal looks at them, laughs, and exclaims, \"Not guilty!\" with a huge guffaw. They walk to a coach waiting on the street.</p><p>A successful DC 12 Wisdom (Perception) check reveals the barrister is holding a child's doll. That should be enough to raise the officers' hackles, but if not, have them roll a DC 14 Wisdom (Insight) check to see if they can tell that the villain is up to something and requires further investigation. If the officers still don't bite, as the coach starts to pull away they hear the muffled screams of a child.</p><p>The officers should stop the coach, free the child and rearrest the villain, this time for kidnapping a child.</p><p>The child is the grandchild of the magistrate, @UUID[Actor.v7F7Xuutb5JtwJk6]{Cyrus Wren}. The thugs kidnapped the girl and gave her doll to the barrister. During the trial the barrister ostentatiously placed the doll on the table, making sure the magistrate saw it and realized what it was. The magistrate quickly found the villain not guilty, hoping that the criminals would release the kid unharmed.</p><p>The magistrate will be forever indebted to the squad for saving his granddaughter.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"sort":350000,"ownership":{"default":0,"dBogmx4vpeLG8Oap":3,"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6":3},"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.2.2","coreVersion":"10.303","createdTime":1683636757666,"modifiedTime":1691035273341,"lastModifiedBy":"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6"},"_id":"omHJShQ5LXmS7pU2"}
{"name":"Player Information","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Campaign Writeup","type":"pdf","_id":"iQ0Rks5MuJ2wT3VM","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":"worlds/the-six-kingdoms/files/Future%20King.pdf","system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6":3},"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.1.5","coreVersion":"10.303","createdTime":1690722683618,"modifiedTime":1690817820485,"lastModifiedBy":"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6"},"_id":"pNsthRlWEpdhCIWN"}
{"folder":"t4OYJx9NxJtOfun3","name":"Case Notes","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Case Notes","type":"text","_id":"ccxpu2HQ6bHsYs1R","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>This journal entry is for the players to add their own notes. You should duplicate it and use the duplicate to avoid overwriting it if you reimport the adventure.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"sort":475000,"ownership":{"default":3,"dBogmx4vpeLG8Oap":3,"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6":3},"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.2.2","coreVersion":"10.303","createdTime":1683049982055,"modifiedTime":1691035273336,"lastModifiedBy":"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6"},"_id":"pVwYwWQkWrc9oL0Y"}
{"folder":"kGo3eJyEM11GvQmk","name":"Goblin Raids","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"The Goblin Raids","type":"text","_id":"kamTe2haoNbGyYgM","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>Goblins have been raiding farms in Kernow. The king decides that it is a task sufficiently challenging to the future king, without much risk of death. Should Arthur die, the queen is still young enough to bear an heir, after all…</p><h2>The Farmstead</h2><p>The prince and his party investigate a farm that was raided by goblins. The house is a smoking shambles, the fields were burned to the ground, and all the animals were butchered and left to rot in the sun.</p><p>Yet somehow, miraculously, the family survived. The goblins attacked in the dead of night, but the mother, Holly, was up feeding the baby when she heard a noise outside. In the bright moonlight she saw the goblins sneaking toward the house. She woke her husband, Sion, and they sneaked into the root cellar with their four children.</p><p>The goblins torched the place, killed the animals, and left, dragging some of the animals they killed.</p><p>They left a trail and made no attempt to hide it. A mistake or an intentional lure? A DC 12 Survival check will lead the group to their camp, about five miles away.</p><h2>Goblin Camp</h2><p>On a DC 12 Investigation check the group realizes that the goblins are carrying weapons made of high-quality Saxon steel, not the iron weapons they normally use. Did they steal them from Saxons, and if so where were the Saxons when they were stolen, or did the Saxons give the goblins the weapons?</p><p>If the party leaves a goblin alive to question, it will not know the answer to that. A successful DC 12 Intimidation or Persuasion check will wring the location of the goblins' base camp out of the survivor. Otherwise a successful DC 18 Survival check will reveal the week-old track the goblins took from their home base, which is another 10 miles into the wild hills of Devon.</p><h2>Gnoll Den</h2><p>Along the way the party runs into a group of gnolls that have just raided the sheep from a farm.</p><h2>Goblin Settlement</h2><p>The party continues following the goblins. They find a bigger camp, with a hobgoblin leader. If the party watches, they will see him dispatching several goblin bands into the night to attack farms. This, fortunately, leaves the camp mostly unprotected.</p><p>If defeated, the hobgoblin will quickly cough up this information: they were given weapons by a group of bugbears, with the instruction to raid the countryside, burn farms, kill and steal animals, but don't kill humans unless threatened by them. </p><p>If a DC 12 Insight check is made the party will realize that they want there to be survivors and refugees. They want to overwhelm Tintagel with refugees from around the countryside. They want to make Uther look weak, that he can't protect them. But how could <em>bugbears</em> come up with such a nefarious plan?</p><p>The hobgoblin leader will tell the party where they meet the bugbears to receive new weapons and marching orders for what areas to hit next.</p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6":3},"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.2.2","coreVersion":"10.303","createdTime":1693281811701,"modifiedTime":1693283299275,"lastModifiedBy":"iYhcliJUezyQtIm6"},"_id":"qSIOik11vSnHh7nN"}
